## Step 5: Test with Thunder Client

### Test 1: Shorten a URL
```
Method: POST
URL: http://localhost:5000/api/shorten
Body (JSON):
{
  "longUrl": "https://www.google.com/search?q=url+shortener+system+design",
  "expiresInDays": 7
}
```

**Expected Response:**
```json
{
  "message": "URL shortened successfully!",
  "shortUrl": "http://localhost:5000/aB3xYz",
  "shortCode": "aB3xYz",
  "longUrl": "https://www.google.com/search?q=url+shortener+system+design",
  "expiresAt": "2026-07-02T..."
}
```

### Test 2: Visit Short URL
```
Open browser → go to: http://localhost:5000/aB3xYz
```
You should be redirected to Google!

### Test 3: Get URL Info
```
Method: GET
URL: http://localhost:5000/api/info/aB3xYz
```

### Test 4: Test Invalid URL
```
Method: POST
URL: http://localhost:5000/api/shorten
Body: { "longUrl": "not-a-url" }
```
Should return error: "Invalid URL format"

---

## 301 vs 302 — Deep Dive (Interview Goldmine)

| | 301 Permanent | 302 Temporary |
|---|---|---|
| **Browser behavior** | Caches the redirect forever | Always asks server |
| **Analytics** | Next click goes directly to destination — server never knows | Every click hits your server — you can count them |
| **SEO** | Passes link juice to destination | Doesn't pass link juice |
| **When to use** | "This URL has moved permanently" | "Redirect may change" |

**For URL shorteners → always use 302**
> You want EVERY click to hit your server so you can record analytics.
> With 301, the browser caches and never tells you about subsequent clicks.

---

## ✅ Phase 2 Checklist

- [ ] `server/utils/shortCode.js` created (Base62 generator)
- [ ] `server/controllers/url.controller.js` created
- [ ] `server/routes/url.routes.js` created
- [ ] `server/index.js` updated with routes
- [ ] POST /api/shorten works → returns short URL
- [ ] GET /:code redirects to long URL
- [ ] Analytics records saved in MongoDB
- [ ] Check MongoDB Compass — see `urls` and `analytics` collections

---

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Interview Question:** "Why 302 and not 301 for a URL shortener?"
> Answer: "302 ensures every redirect request hits the server, allowing us to track analytics. 301 would be cached by browsers, making subsequent clicks invisible to our analytics pipeline."

